mes © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Lascelles","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from one of the large number of places in northern France called Celle, Celles, Lacelle, Leschelle, or Lachelle, all from French <i>celle</i> ‘hermitage’, and at different times occurring both with and without the plural <i>-s</i>.","Variant of   Lacelle   1, a surname of French origin."],"variants":[{"name":"Laswell","meanings":["English: possibly an altered form of   Lascelles  . This surname is also found as   Lacefield  ."]},{"name":"Lasell","meanings":["English: variant of   Lascelles  ."]},{"name":"Lacelle","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alain, Andre, Aurele, Benoit, Cecile, Marcel, Marie Paule.","Altered form of French <b>Laselle</b>: habitational name from La Selle, the name of several places in various parts of France. The surname <i>Laselle</i> is very rare in France, found in Marne. Compare   Lascelles  .","In some cases possibly also French: habitational name from Lacelle in Corrèze or numerous minor places called La Celle, all named for a monastic cell or hermitage in their vicinity, from French <i>celle</i> ‘hermitage’."]}]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Walther","meanings":["from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’; name of the famous medieval minnesinger  Walther von der Vogelweide  (  <i>c.</i>1170– <i>c.</i>1230 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":42,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Walter de Lascelles was born in 1340, in Yorkshire, England, his father, Sir Walter de Lascelles of Escrick, was 41 and his mother, Agnes Radcliffe, was 19. He married Isabell Eland about 1393, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1392, in his hometown, at the age of 52."},"et":{"1340–1392":"1340–1392","1394–Male":"1394–Surnud","1350–Female":"1350–Surnud","1360–1428":"1360–1428","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","1321–Female":"1321–Surnud","1300":"1300","1321":"1321","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","1394":"1394","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1392":"1392","Abt 1339":"umbes 1339","1428":"1428","Escrick, , Yorkshire, England":"Escrick, Yorkshire, England","East Riding, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Escryck, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"1340–1392":"1340–1392","1394–Male":"1394–Kuollut","1350–Female":"1350–Kuollut","1360–1428":"1360–1428","1300–Male":"1300–Kuollut","1321–Female